y and her Imagination Library.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/cK7ymuw</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/oW7IZ79.png" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>In 1995, Dolly Parton founded the Imagination Library, which to this day has delivered books to millions of children free of charge. But did you know that in the 1930s, librarians themselves took up the saddle to deliver free books to children?

Dolly herself has said that she has said she was inspired by her deep love of reading and by her father, who was not able to read or write, to bring books to children and support their dreams. "The seeds of these dreams are often found in books," Parton says on the program's website, "and the seeds you help plant in your community can grow across the world.”

That sentiment has always rung true in Appalachia, no matter how remote. Pack Saddle Librarians, known by their patrons as "The Bookwomen," walked so that Dolly could run—proof that Appalachian communities have been showing up for each other in unique and creative ways for a long time.

The “Bookwomen,” also known as “book ladies” and “pack saddle librarians,” were librarians of the “Pack Horse Library Project,” a division of the WPA (Works Progress Administration), a program instituted by President Franklin Roosevelt between 1935 and 1943 to boost the economy by paying people for services during the Great Depression.

